<br>
I was born in Texas, raised in Arizona.  So no flag around me, and not much to do with the North/South thing.  There are bigots in Arizona.  There are bigots in Nevada.     <br>
<br>
However, I drove across country this past April.  I was sickened by some of the ignorance that I fell witness to.  Most of it came from family members, warning me away from certain places.  Why?  Because the neighborhood color wasn't white.  <br>
<br>
One relative flipped out when they found out we were stopping at an A&amp;W for lunch in New Mexico on an INDIAN RES OMG!!!  <br>
<br>
We met really really nice people, and saw beautiful places.  And the A&amp;W lunch was great <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://jens-smileys.netfirms.com/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
I think that primarily the flag is a symbol of Southern pride, that the South was soveriegn.. like Texas once was, and they are proud of that too.<br>
<br>
However, this flag's history bears a strong burden of guilt.  Guilt that isn't easily forgotten, and the history behind it hurts some people.  <br>
<br>
I don't know what the answer to that is.  Getting rid of the flag would be wrong.  It is a part of history.  Educating people and erasing this fucking ignorance that is EVERYWHERE in this country would be a good start.  Rhaiq displays it because he is proud of his Southern roots.  If everyone displayed it for the same reason, or viewed it with the same outlook it would be okay.  <br>
<br>
Unfortunately, there is no Santa.  <br>
