That last part I'll agree with. I don't always agree with the NAACP because I feel that now and then, the representatives can be as full of BS as the next political organization in line.<br>
<br>
I still stand that the flag is a harsh reminder of our dirty past. From the ashes of the civil war sprang such lovely groups as the ku klux klan. They've used the confederate flag as one of their symbols (which they're fond of) more strongly since the 60s as a slap in the face of the civil rights movement.<br>
<br>
I do find this topic somewhat interesting. Right now I'm going through the ringer with my girlfriend's father who, despite &quot;I have black friends,&quot; is an amazing racist. He admits this. He knows it's wrong but, and I quote &quot;I just feel that blacks and whites should be separate.&quot; His words not mine.<br>
<br>
Personally, I'm more a chai-cinnamon mocca grande Starbucks kinda guy.<br>
<br>
Those that carry the flag or don't care... bear with us that do have a negative reaction to it. Some of us have a lifetime of negative interactions and experiences that have given us pavlovian knee-jerk reactions towards symbols like this one. <br>
<br>
It's hard to separate the *Hatred* from the *Heritage* on the matter of this flag. <p>*****<BR>
